So when the user clicks "Show Answer" (either via a button, gesture, or the showAnswer() JavaScript function), it directly calls `displayCardAnswer()` without first capturing the input from the HTML input tag.Let me look at the displayCardAnswer method again to see if there's any code to capture the input before displaying the answer:

From lines 1308-1346 of AbstractFlashcardViewer.kt:
```kotlin
open fun displayCardAnswer() {
    // ... (lines 1309-1321)    
    typeAnswer!!.updateInfo(getColUnsafe, currentCard!!, resources)
    // ... (lines 1324-1329)
    displayAnswer = true
    answerField!!.visibility = View.GONE
    // Clean up the user answer and the correct answer    if (!typeAnswer!!.useInputTag) {
        typeAnswer!!.input = answerField!!.text.toString()
    }
    isSelecting = false    val answerContent = htmlGenerator!!.generateHtml(getColUnsafe, currentCard!!, SingleCardSide.BACK)
    // ... (rest)
}
```

So at line 1333-1335, it only captures the input from `answerField` (the Android EditText) if `!typeAnswer!!.useInputTag`. If `useInputTag` is true, it doesn't capture the input at all!

This means that when `useInputTag` is true, the `typeAnswer.input` will only be set if the user previously triggered a taBlur or taKey event. If the user clicks "Show Answer" without pressing Enter or causing the input to lose focus, the input won't be captured.The fix should be to capture the input value from the HTML input element before displaying the answer. This can be done using JavaScript to get the value and pass it to Android, or by using WebView's evaluateJavascript method.Let me check if there's any existing JavaScript code to get the input value.

